      "message": "Optimizers can catch on to this trick, even with “volatile.” I’d suggest using __builtin_trap() since we don’t really care which hardware fault is taken, although SetExpectedChildTermination() does want a specific signal to match, and __builtin_trap() will sometimes be SIGILL and sometimes SIGTRAP (and in theory, sometimes other values). util/posix/signals_test.cc has a refresher.\n\n(Along the same lines of that parenthetical theory, the SIGSEGV that you’ve used here could also be other things, most likely SIGBUS, depending mostly on CPU.)\n\nWe can still use __builtin_trap() but provide a constant near SetExpectedChildTermination() that contains the signal number effectively raised by __builtin_trap(). If a constant won’t do because there’s a runtime dependency (kernel version, kernel bitness, etc.), we could do a runtime function to calculate the value where needed, or we could roll it into a new SetExpectedChildTerminationBuiltinTrap() function instead of exposing a constant.\n\nSame at line 285, with implications on lines 105 and 268.",
